comments.commentBody:
@JJGG: Not for the first time, I find myself reading thoughts that you have attributed to me, that I myself have never written. If you care to react to something that I have *actually* written, feel free to do so. I relish the back and forth, and I'm a big boy and can defend myself. Let's see, what I wrote about Onyewu was that he was "scary bad." In what way do you choose to interpret that to mean that I "would say always needs a second chance?" You have absolutely no place to place words in my mouth or thoughts in my head. You have enough trouble coming up with coherent thoughts on your own, mate.<br/>
Speaking of your precious Italians, do you care to place a wager on them having a better Euro tournament than England? We are now at two match fixing scandals in six years, and three in 30. What other country has this track record? The new Italian Prime Minister has suggested suspending Serie A for two or three seasons (link: <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/30/world/europe/monti-suggests-suspending-soccer-in-italy-after-scandal.html)" title="http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/30/world/europe/monti-suggests-suspending-soccer-in-italy-after-scandal.html)" target="_blank">http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/30/world/europe/monti-suggests-suspending...</a><br/>
Italy got thrashed by Russia and whistled off the pitch by a pro Italy crowd in Switzerland, and, after the match, Prandelli floated the idea of withdrawing from Euro 2012. Care to comment on YOUR side, JJGG? OTOH, 44 years since winning the tournament, a match fixing scandal, a squad loaded with Juve players coming off of a Scudetto...Sounds just like 1982 (or 2006, except Juve's Scudetto was vacated that time for fixing)...
